blog.description: I probably read too many comics. Here are some highlights. If you like, go give money to the creators.

summary: This issue is an excellent cap- no pun intended- to a relatively long run (I think- it’s hard to keep track, since Marvel...
caption:
This issue is an excellent cap- no pun intended- to a relatively long run (I think- it’s hard to keep track, since Marvel ensured it had approximately a million number ones in the space of not much time, because that is their thing for some reason). It’s very much a character-centered issue, and strikes a perfect balance of funny and sad, more celebratory than mournful, something that this panel captures rather well.

DeConnick resolves the key plot points of her run, and leaves enough for the next writer to be able to start afresh or maintain a strong sense of continuity. Given that Secret Wars then did the whole cosmic event thing after this, and the All-New, All-Different Marvel relaunch (hey kids! Another number one!) followed, I guess that this sort of conclusion was not necessary, but I really enjoy it when a writer’s run ends like this. It gives you the satisfying impression that they told the story they wanted to tell, and are happy to move on and leave the character to new adventures from another team- I think it emphasises both the ongoing nature of comics, characters continuing exist regardless of who’s at the helm, and the importance of a good story and the feeling that a creative team are putting their heart into the work because they are being allowed to tell the tale they want to. It also suggests some thoughtful planning has gone into things at the publisher- there’s nothing worse than the times when some kind of event-based reboot comes up and story-lines are just unceremoniously dropped, or awkwardly wound up in about a tenth of the time they clearly needed. To me, this run’s end was handled just the way it should be (if it had to end), giving a satisfying conclusion with no sense of things abandoned due to circumstances- the only real disappointment is that the writer of so many fine issues is gone.

Of course, whatever comes next, however All-New, All-Different it aims to be, Kelly Sue better not have run off with Chewie. I want the Carol and Chewie Corps or I will be very very upset.

From Captain Marvel 15, by Kelly Sue DeConnick, David Lopez, Lee Loughridge & Joe Caramagna

title: Disney Play, el servicio de streaming de la compañía, es prioridad ahora, dice el CEO
body:
Disney Play, el servicio de streaming de la compañía, es prioridad ahora, dice el CEO

El próximo servicio de transmisión de Disney finalmente tiene un nombre tentativo, y se informa que es la prioridad número uno de la compañía en 2019.

El CEO de Disney, Bob Iger, se refiere al servicio de transmisión de Disney como Disney Play, según Variety, y el servicio está orientado como rival de los principales competidores, principalmente Netflix y Amazon. Hay otra aplicación llamada Play…
